The faults are so numerous and of such a nature, that one must doubt, whether the scribe understood Latin. Yet the faults which spring from his misunderstanding and careless writing (few of which can be corrected vvith absolute certainty) impair the value of the MS. less than his numerous omissions.

Single words, parts of sentences, and probably even long pas- sages are missing. In consequence of these omissions the text in many places gives no sense, and correction is rendered more difficult by the impossibility of deciding whether the omissions are of single words or of sentences,
